\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under severe inequalities 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- a case study in Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role played by wealth
 inequalities and spatial exclusion in the varied contexts of developing
 economies is explored less often.
 We develop a model for status consumption considering permanent ownership
 and high quality the primary indicators of status in a framework of intertempor
al substitution.
 Incorporating the opposite effects of peer influences and extreme wealth
 differences on status competitions in the model, we use the data on durable
 goods ownership from the Tanzanian LSMS consumption microdata to discuss
 how a segregation of overall quality in an environment of price heterogeneity
 may characterise status consumption in a developing economy.
\end_layout

