\begin_layout Standard
If we could consider the social identities in the same ranking order as
 of wealth, the consumption beyond fulfillment of needs could be viewed
 as the consumer's attempt to alter the wealth order.
 However, however are two problems with this approach.
 First is that the social identities (tribes, castes, race etc.) may not
 always be observed as crisp categories of wealth.
 Second, the social identities are always associated with a particular scope
 and the competitions to reach a higher status may also be separated by
 the scope of social identities.
 While some social identities could be perceived to be of higher status
 than others, it is also true that individuals that are too poor or too
 different from other groups might not compare themselves with those that
 are either too rich or too different from themselves.
 This does complicate the role that social identities plays towards consumption
 as they both i) limit the status consumption within themselves and ii)
 carry a status value to those outside the respective social groups.
 Notice that it is only outside the reference group driven by one's identity
 that a social identity may influences status the way wealth differences
 would.
 Within the scope of the social identity that determines a reference group,
 the social identity doesn't carry much status to those in the reference
 group (since everybody carries the same social identity).
 Therefore when a social identity - which determines a reference group -
 also limits competitions for status within itself, one may no longer assume
