 and permanent ownership.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, a consumer changes her status by achieving both permanent
 ownership of goods and relative quality.
 If status is viewed as a ranking order based on long-term characteristics
 such as income, education and other social characteristics, the consumers
 are to compete with each other in order to offset the deep wealth and social
 hierarchies that determine the ranking order (see Corneo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In an empirical analysis, the two status indicator variables whose measurement
 is critical to the model's operationalisation are i) the wealth of a consumer
 which we could proxy relatively easily in a developing economy if the stock
 of durable goods the consumer has (inclusive of housing, land and other
 long-term assets) is made available and ii) the quality in non-durable
 consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within non-durable consumptin, we only consider quality's contribution towards
 status because the fulfillment of basic needs alone is not expected to
 offer any advantage in a status competition.
 More specifically, a consumer with a habit of 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) would have higher status than another consumer consuming less
 quality if the needs of the two consumers are the same.
 As long as a common set of basic consumer needs can be assumed for two
 consumers, there is no status utility to be achieved through addressing
 of needs alone.
 The claim has a particular implication for our model of utility - if there
 is any status related utility to be derived from non-durable consumption,
 it would be constituted in the felicity from 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
quality (which is defined as distance from all needs tied to a particular
 reference group).
 It also follows that any status in a particular reference group that is
 not signaled with quality in non-durable consumption must come out of the
 possession of (and thus utility from) the long-term durable goods (or the
 proxy of wealth).
 Life-cycle assumptions are thus implicitly included in the model as long
 we can view a durable good as one that can be passed on to the progeny.
\end_layout

