 driven etc.).
 As these are hardly available in a typical consumption dataset, we consider
 an elaboration of the model where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is observed at the level of groups defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The following subsection first discusses how the variables identified so
 far outline a model for status using a direct utility approach - vis-a-vis
 how the consumer utility depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\frac{c_{t}-\Psi-P_{\psi}\psi}{P_{\nu}}$
\end_inset

.
 We then elaborate a cost-function-based approach that relaxes the limitations
 imposed by the direct utility model and considers 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 observed at a 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

-group level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Intertemporal Substitution with an additive direct utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we can assume that the needs of the consumer evolve with a deterministic
 process 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 that is known to the consumer, the substitution would be limited only between
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 in the direct utility model.
 The assumption is not implausible in a developing economy.
 Given such a substitution between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, one could write the combined utility as an additive loglinear utilty in
 the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\upsilon(\rho,A,\nu,\psi) & =k_{A}log(s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A))+k_{\psi}log(\psi)+k_{\nu}log(\nu)+k_{\rho}log(\int_{\rho}A)\label{eq:loglinearutil}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A}+k_{\psi}+k_{\nu}+k_{\rho}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A clear limitation of the above model is that the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,A,\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 do not represent how the longer-term choices may constrain the short-term
 choices.
 More particularly, the longer-term choices are not only more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

permanent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that guard one's status - they also open possibilities of
 status-signalling through (non-durable) means (i.e.
 less permanent than the durable goods).
 A particular state or characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 of the consumer could constraint or enhance the available choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, much the way 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 may constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 For example, having an urban residence opens up the access to a wider market
 for status goods.
 In household-related consumption, similarly, the high prices of housing
 may encourage a consumer to upgrade accessories such as furniture (thus
 increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 However, she may improve the overall quality instead of buying a bigger
 house only until a certain point - beyond which she may need a bigger house
 (
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 ) to improve the furniture etc.
 (thus being encouraged to save for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 again).
 This implies that the consumers with lower weight for 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 may compensate by increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 but only as much.
 The effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is both due to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

herd-effect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a consequence of the costs that are imposed by the durable goods one possesses
 (e.g.
 fuel for cars, electricity for heating equipment, rent/maintenance-fees
 for housing etc.).
 In the direct utility approach, one can treat such constraints as part
 of the needs cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such constraints on choices that we incorporate in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 are not entirely unrelated to the temporal hierarchy since the constraints
 are essentially the part of commitment implied by the consumer's long-term
 choice.
 Certain costs are necessarily associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 - both of which (along with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 if a consumer could change her characteristics) are long-term commitments
 of the consumer.
 If a consumer chooses to be on a trajectory of higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumer might have less concerns for status (a choice where life-cycle
 effects have a direct influence).
 Similarly, the ownership of durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 also presents a commitment to costs associated with the owned durable good
 - albeit less inescapable than 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

( since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 can be sold in the market or rented out for income).
 The constraints which choices present are thus also part of the temporal
 hierarchy we have outlined in the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moving further into the dynamics of the model, we assume that at the end
 of the lifetime of a consumer, the personal wealth of the consumer would
 either be consumed or would be passed on to her progeny so that the asset
 account at the end of the lifetime becomes starting wealth of some other
 household(s) in the economy.
 Consequently, all consumers in the population differ in the the starting
 amount of their asset accounts as well as the trends of their salaries.
 If a consumer has a starting income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 and her salary after 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau-\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 years of working is 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 then at a given age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (the start of working age is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

), she could have purchased some long-term durable-goods from a portion
 of her income - deciding that she does not want more durable goods for
 the rest of her life.
 Alternatively, she could have experienced a change in the life-circumstances
 (needing a bigger or a more expensive house) thus needing more durable
 goods urgently.
 The consumption in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would therefore depend on the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, asset account value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and the consumption of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Due to minimal presence of credit facilities in the developing countries,
 we assume an environment of negligible credit.
 This in turn implies that the consumer can only save to buy more of the
 only durable goods available in the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider how two consumers that are vastly separated by their
 respective characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho_{1}}A<\int_{\rho_{2}}A$
\end_inset

 or vice versa) might behave in the direct utility model.
 Recall that the utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (weight 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\rho})$
\end_inset

 means that someone with a group that has a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 an urbanite or someone in a privileged social class) would be believed
 to be rich - even though her real wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 might be at same level with someone with a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 a rural person or someone with an underprivileged social class).
 What permits the decomposition of utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into those through 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 is the social observation (i.e.
 perception) of individuals in terms of identities that are established
 through long-term political or economic events.
 Thus an urbanite or someone with a privileged social class might not need
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth to indicate a higher status when compared with a rural person or
 someone from an under-privileged class who may have the same or even higher
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth.
 Yet since competitions for status matter within one's own social reference
 group and since inference of status is through social observation (perception),
 the individuals from respective social classes would continue to compare
 themselves within the same social reference group as well as those outside
 their social reference group - implying the relevance of both 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 in the common utility function
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While we assume static 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 in the empirical analyses, the separate effects also accommodate the change
 in demand of quality as one changes their social reference group (e.g.
 by moving residence or establishing social networks outsides one's reference
 group).
 In such a case, the consumer changing 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has to to adjust to the higher (or lower) 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (due to a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A,\rho)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The separate effects of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 also explain how the differences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 could dominate to such an extent that competing with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,A$
\end_inset

 might not matter towards status competitions (we explore the condition
 of this separation in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Cost-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the direct utility function specified in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:loglinearutil"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we can now specify a simple intertemporal substitution framework where
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t},\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 are the respective measures for needs, quality and durable goods in the
 time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 If the consumer faced only two periods, then the utilities to be maximised
 in the two periods would be described as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
u_{1}=k_{\psi}log(\psi_{1})+k_{\rho}log(\int_{\rho}A)+k_{\nu,1}log(\nu_{1})+k_{A,1}log(s(A_{1})-m(\int_{\rho}A))\label{eq:twoperiodoptim}\\
u_{2}=k_{\psi}log(\psi_{2})+k_{\rho}log(\int_{\rho}A)+k_{\nu,2}log(\nu_{2})+k_{A,2}log(s(A_{2})-m(\int_{\rho}A))\nonumber 
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 are consumption on quality in periods 1 and 2 respectively while 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 are value of durable goods at start of the periods 1 and 2.
 The constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\psi}+k_{\rho}+k_{\nu,i}+k_{A,i}=1$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ge0$
\end_inset

) apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equilibrium, we consider that the utility from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are fixed and can thus be assumed to be predetermined for the consumer.
 The consumer choice is therefore not exercised for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is not far-fetched in a developing economy.
 However, outside the developing economy contexts, if needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 expansion of family) were to be treated as part of the consumer choice,
 we may consider that an individual could delay or suspend the expansion
 of family in order to fulfill a target 
\begin_inset Formula $A-m(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 The basic needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and the utility one gets from 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 for a rich and poor individual may be the same but the costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A,\rho)$
\end_inset

 the two may face depends both on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 When faced with imminent expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, therefore the consumer could discourage potential changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 so as to maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $A-m(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 (by keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

.
 This effect is indeed ignored with the assumption of a predetermined 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 being predetermined for every consumer in the economy implies that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 is nearly constant with time, the consumer exercises her choice only by
 distributing income between 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu_{1},A_{1}-m(\int_{\rho_{1}}A))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu_{2},A_{2}-m(\int_{\rho_{2}}A))$
\end_inset

 in a two-period model.
 The only true substitution - in other words - is between 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a typical solution of the intertemporal problem, the wealth constraint
 for the optimisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $U=u_{0}+u_{1}$
\end_inset

 would consider the final 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 all of the consumer's durable goods being liquidated and consumed in the
 last period) and the discounting rate based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 - but in our case, we prefer to track the change in asset account 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 at every period i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{t}=A_{t}-A_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 (as we observe ownership of durable goods rather than wealth).
 Using a dynamic optimisation formulation, we write the following constraints:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
J_{1}\equiv x_{1}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{1},A_{1})=(P_{\nu,1}\psi_{1})\nu_{1}+\Delta_{1}P_{A,1}\nonumber \\
J_{2}\equiv x_{2}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{2},A_{2})=(P_{\nu,2}\psi_{2})\nu_{2}+\Delta_{2}P_{A,2}\label{eq:J_constraints}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A,i}$
\end_inset

 is the price of durable-goods in period 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu,i}$
\end_inset

 represents the price non-durable quality respectively (not associated with
 a particular item with quality overall).
 The above means that the consumer may consume quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{3...}$
\end_inset

 being undefined) in the periods 1 and 2 while she bears the cost of the
 needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(\rho,\psi_{1},A_{1}),\Psi(\rho,\psi_{2},A_{2})$
\end_inset

 (in periods 1 and 2 respectively).
 She may save for growth to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}=A_{0}+P_{A,1}\Delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}=A_{1}+P_{A,2}\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of consuming all her outlay 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=\nu_{t}\psi_{t}+\Psi_{t}(\psi_{t},A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 she can spend all of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) or save some of it towards 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we observe the states of the wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{1},c_{2}\},$
\end_inset

 cost of necessities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}\}$
\end_inset

, the prices of quality units (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu,t}$
\end_inset

) and that of durable goods (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A,t}$
\end_inset

), then we can solve for the parameters that govern the utility function
 additive over time i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we assume that the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 grow with a fixed deterministic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

, the outlay to be distributed in expenditure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t},A_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{t}=x_{t}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{t},A_{t})$
\end_inset

 (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:J_constraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 To motivate the dynamic programming approach to this solution, consider
 first what consumer's choices would be in a one-period consumption.
 Here, she could either spend her outlay as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{_{1}}=\nu_{1}\psi_{1}+\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 or keep the minimum consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0,c_{1}=\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

) in the period and end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, then the first-order conditions would provide us the optimal condition
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this utility be 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}^{*},A_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To extend this to two periods with dynamic optimisation one can exploit
 the fact that a consumer independently optimising 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 would always obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 are unbounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $max(u_{1}+u_{2})\le max(u_{1})+max(u_{2})=u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 is only a tool to formulate the dynamic optimisation approach - using which
 the value of utility is to be optimised over her life period in a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-period model (
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being the age of the consumer).
 Thus in the optimisation of utility function in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:twoperiodoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the consumer must optimise both 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 in periods 1 and 2 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have put no restrictions on 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu,2}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A,1},k_{A,2})$
\end_inset

 (other than that they should add to unity in every period).
 If we add some structure to the consumer choice by introducing life-cycle
 effects with a form of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu},k_{A}$
\end_inset

 that depends on the age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of the consumer - so the same level of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 offers less utility to the consumer as shes age (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 declines with age) and that the same level of long-term durable goods has
 higher utility later in life (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A}$
\end_inset

 increases with age).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu},k_{A}$
\end_inset

 could be assumed to be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $n(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau)$
\end_inset

 - functions that known to the consumer that vary with the age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of the consumer - a sensitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau,A)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 could be considered.
 In economies that are segregated based on long-term durable goods that
 are largely intergenerational (and thus long-term enough for their utility
 to not change over time), the sensitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau,A)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 may be very little and could allow us to use a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The first-order conditions using the Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:twoperiodoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:J_constraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 above give us the following Marshallian demand function in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{t},P_{A,t},P_{\nu,t}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
P_{A,t}\Delta_{t}=k_{A,t}(J_{t}-P_{A,t}m(\int_{\rho}A))\nonumber \\
P_{\nu,t}\psi_{t}\nu_{t}=k_{A,t}(J_{t}-P_{A,t}m(\int_{\rho}A))\label{eq:DirectUtilityMarshallian}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above solution highlights how a substitution between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 may be influenced by social charactersitics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and life-cycle effects.
 An obvious implication is that higher needs suppress the total outlay for
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Also evident is that in absolute terms, the richer consumers would find
 it more expensive to indicate wealth to their surrounding.
 The equivalent argument applies for quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Assumed an appropriate form for 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A,t}$
\end_inset

 would show that the consumer would increase her ownership of durable goods
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A,t}$
\end_inset

 increases with time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are however three major limitations to such an approach.
 First is that using a loglinear utility, the price derivatives of the cost-func
tion need to be the same for both subsistence and bliss (see Appendix for
 details).
 Second, the issue of constraints imposed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - which we've discussed above - is not sufficiently addressed with the
 additive function.
 The third and probably the most critical limitation is that we have assumed
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 to be uniform for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Since the price of relative quality of non-durable consumption in excess
 of needs (relevant for status consumption) is likely to depend on long-term
 characteristics e.g.
 wealth measure 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 or characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 such as residence or social class in an economy, the empirical utility
 of the model is limited.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many reasons why the cost of relative quality could differ significant
ly across regions.
 One such instance is the unavailability of certain high-quality items in
