 Recorded by the survey at two different time-points spread across two years
 (let's call the time points 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

), these reported costs may change over the period of two years - i.e.
 the reported cost of the same durable good in 2012 (
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) can be significantly different from the cost reported in 2014 (
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

).
 This may simply be because of a different member of the same household
 providing the estimate in the two different years.
 The problem gets worsened due to two further factors.
 First, that the data we have from the three waves are not panel-data in
 the true sense since the household visited in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

